Short thread on bedroom interior design.

First: walls should never be pure white, but never a solid colour. Anything pastelish or diluted is fine, but white walls will reflect any rogue light that comes from outside, they are the one thing to avoid. Very light blue is best.

When falling asleep, the window/door to the outside should be in your direct field of vision. Our instincts make us always wary of intruders, you need to watch the entrance to your chamber, otherwise your sleep will be plagued by anxieties.

* The bed HAS to be next to a wall. *

Your back to the wall, your eyes slowly closing while looking to the one possible path of an attacker.

There should be no mirrors in your bedroom, or they should be hidden at nighttime. Mirrors are not what they seem, and entities and energies might come and go through them.

The cardinal direction your head and and feet point toward matters - the alignment with the electromagnetic fields of the earth.

Some say being perpendicular (head towards East) is most relaxing and cooling, but others prefer having their head towards South, which promotes ...

Henry Box Brown, the black American man who mailed himself away from slavery, shares some interesting typological parallels with Jesus - he was 33 years old when he performed the escape, you can see the symbolism of rebirth in being locked in the box (think of Jonah and the fish)

The first thing he did when he exited the box was apparently singing Psalm 40, a slightly modified version, it's even on the Wikipedia page, very curious case, not sure how famous it is with current Americans though
